IRS990.Description: WIC is designed to improve children's nutrition during critical periods of development and is a resource for parents to establish healthy eating habits that last a lifetime. This cost-effective, successful public health program meets an urgent need for nutrition care for low-income women and their children in high-risk groups, and educates families about making healthy food choices, reducing childhood obesity, and maintaining healthy weight through sound nutrition. WIC was established in 1974 to promote good nutrition for children and expectant mothers and has earned the reputation of being one of the most successful, cost-effective, federally-funded nutrition programs in the United States. Today, WIC has become a key component of the safety net system for low-income and special needs families and functions as a vital link in our efforts to ensure all children have a healthy start. With participation levels at an all time high, the program continues to change and adapt to meet the needs of the families we serve. Half of the children born in the United States are served by the WIC Program, and in Pennsylvania, MFHS serves one quarter of all WIC participants. WIC promotes breastfeeding as the most perfect infant food, and provides support for new mothers who choose to breastfeed. The MFHS WIC Breastfeeding Peer Counselor Program works to increase breastfeeding initiation and duration rates for WIC participants. Peer counselors provide new mothers with support and encouragement during the early post-partum period and help them make the transition back to work or school. WIC is a program for pregnant and breastfeeding women, and infants and children up to age 5. Income guidelines apply. WIC is a program of the Pennsylvania Department of Health with funds from the United States Department of Agriculture. WIC is an equal opportunity provider. Over 59,500 per month are served, an increase of 1.3% over the previous year.

Activity2.Description: Family Planning, General/Other: Family planning provides qality reproductive health care, education and counseling for women, men and youn adults. Care is provided regardless of income, by skilled health care professionals offering a complete range of reproductive health services inncluding: gynecological and pelvic exams, cerrvical and breast cancer screening, testing and treatment fro sexually transmitted diseases, access to birth control, pregnancy testing, counseling and referals. (35,798 clients annually) Funding is provided by Title X of the Public Health Services Act, Title XX, Title V and Medicaid reimbursements.

Activity3.Description: Health Care Delivery & Management: Nurse Family Partnership program is an evidence based program which guides at risk, first time mothers through pregnancy and provides support during the critical first two years of the childs life. Services are offered in Lackawanna, Luzeren, Wayne and Susquehannao Counties. (347 families currenlty enrolled) Funding sources include a grant from the Pennsylvania Department of Public Welfare, Office of Child Development and Early Lerning as well as Medical Assistance reimbursements.

ActivityOther.Description: Infectious Diseases Programs, General/Other: Infertility Prevention Project provides for the screeing and treatment of chlymadia in low income women throughout Pennsylvania. (52,000 clients annually) Funding is provided by a grant from the Center for Disease Control via the Pennsylvania Department of Public Health.

Women's Cancer Programs: Program provides preventative screenings and disgnostic services for breast and cervical cancer to women between the ages of 40 and 64 with low to moderate income who do not have alternative medical insurance. (1,778 clients served). Funding sources include the Healthy Women prgoram from the U.S. Center fro Disease Control via the Pennsylvania Deparment of Health, the Norteast pennsylvania Affiliate of Susan G. Komen for the Cure and the Avon Foundation.

Reproductive Health Programs, General/Other: Healthy Beginnings Plus is a prenatal program which takes a postitive, proactive role in ensuring a healthy pregnancy. The comprehensive package of servcies includes medical and social services, that are essential for health birth outcomes, especially among mothers with high risk pregencies. (403 clients annually). Funding is provided by the Pennsylvania Department of Welfare via an expanded eligibility and scope of service through medical assistance. In additon MFHS offers infant and childhood checkups at the Circle of Care Health Center, Scranton, in partnership with Dr. Linda Thomas-Hemak and The Wright Center for Primary Care. The well-baby and well-child checkups are offered once a week at Circle of Care as part of the Early and Periodic Screening, Diagnosis, and Treatment (EPSDT) program for Medicaid eligible babies and children. EPSDT is the child health component of Medicaid designed to improve the health of low-income children through appropriate and necessary pediatric services. The partnership with The Wright Center for Primary Care allowed MFHS to 155 well baby visits over the past year, providing preventative care to the families we serve at Circle of Care.

Specialized Human Services Programs, General/Other: A number of minor projects inlcuding tobacco cessation and miscellaneous expenditures not propererly costed in theother projects. (2000 clients served annually.)

GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The CEO is formally evaluated annually by the Executive Committee of the Board of Directors on her anniversary date. This was last done in the fall of 2010. All other key employees are reviewed annually by their immediate supervisor on their anniversary date. The process utilizes a standardized form for general supervisory and management skills. In addition each employee receives a development plan and is assigned specific goals from organizations strategic plan which are evaluated in the subsquent year as to how well they were acheived.
